      "source": [
        "LANGUAGE AI\n",
        "\n",
        "the term AI is used to describe computer systems that an perform certain tasks like speech recognition, language translation, and visual perception close to human intelligence, but AI doesnt need to confine itself to the methods that are biologically observable\n",
        "\n",
        "but sometimes we consider most of the systems as AI which is not the case like the NPC characters in the games most of the times they are just if else statements\n",
        "\n",
        "language ai is a subfield  of AI that focuses on developing technologies that are capable of understanding, processing and generating human languag. the term language AI can often be used in place of NLP as machine learning has also advanced in this field and tackling language processing problems\n",
        "this term also includes technologies which might not be llms but have a notable contribution in the dev of this field like retrieval systems\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "history of language AI\n",
        "\n",
        "see fig 1, many models were made to generate language, but understanding the language is always a difficult task for computers  as it is unstructured for nature and loses its meaning when represented in 0 and 1, and the researchers have focused largely on representing language in a structured way so that computers can understand them easily, see fig 1-2\n",
        "\n",
        "it all started with bag of words, it is a method to represent unstructures text, first came in 1950s but become popular in 2000s\n",
        "\n",
        "the bag of words works in this way :\n",
        "\n",
        "lets say we have two sentences and we want to convert it into numerical representations, the first step is tokenization meaning breaking sentences in small words or subwords (tokens) see fig 1-3\n",
        "the most common way to do this is seperate using blank spaces but some languages like mandarin dont have blank spaces\n",
        "\n",
        "now after the tokenisation we create vocalubary to represent sentences, we do this by combining all unique words\n",
        "\n",
        "from the vocabulary we simply count the how often a word is used in the sentence, this is how we represent text in form of numbers using bag of words, this representation is also called vectors or vector representations see fig 1-5,\n",
        "models like bag of words are referred to as representation models\n",
        "\n",
        "even if its a classic method it is by no means completely unused, we can use this method to complement recent lang models\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "BETTER REPRESENTATIONS WITH DENSE VECTOR EMBEDDINGS\n",
        "\n",
        "bag of words is a good method but it considers language to be nothing but a bag of words only, it doesnt capture the semantic nature of the text like what the text means..\n",
        "\n",
        "word2vec released in 2013 was the first model to capture to meaning of texts in embeddings which are the vector rep of the data that tries to capture the meaning of the data, to  do this word2vec was trained on the vast amounts of textual information like the entire wikipedia\n",
        "\n",
        "to make these sementic rep, word2vec uses neural networks see fig 1-6, using the several interconnected layers to process information, it generates word embeddings by seeing which words tends to come in next after a particular sentence\n",
        "\n",
        "it starts by giving each word in the vocabulary a vector embedding, say 60 values assigned randomly to 60 words\n",
        "then pairs are picked from the training data and the model predicts whether theres a chance they wil appear together in a sentence, see fig 1-7\n",
        "\n",
        "during the training the model learns the relationship between the words and embedd them into the embedding,, if two words are tend to have same neighbours they will have closer embeddings and vice versa\n",
        "\n",
        "when we say the embeddings tries to capture the meaning of the words we mean embeddings try to capture the information by representing the properties of words eg :\n",
        "lets say we have two words \"baby\" and \"apple\", now the baby word will score higher in properties like \"newborn\" and \"human\", and apple will score low in these properties.\n",
        "\n",
        "see fig 1-8 embeddings can have may properties at once as their sizes are fixed and properties help to create a mental representation of the word, it makes sense to a computer and an efficient way to understand and translate the human language\n",
        "\n",
        "through embeddings we can also mesaure the semantic similarity between two words by using various distance based approach to see how close the words are\n",
        "see fig 1-9 it shows the embedding in a 2d space as we can see the words with similar meaning tend to be closer"
      ]
    },
